1 Introduction

Tarr (2024b) looked at the online survey completed voluntarily by the 2024 S2 cohort of DATA2x02, totaling 313 responses for 49 question. The end result is stored in a .xlsx file, exported from Google form. FigureÂ 1. The responses are unlikely to be a completely random sample of DATA2x02 students. Since the survey is completed voluntarily on Edstem, the survey is subject to non-random participation. This survey may over-represent students who are interested in the subject and those who frequently open their Ed discussions.

Aside from the bias mentioned above, many variables in this survey are subject to other biases. Questions regarding WAM and others of similar sensitive nature are subject to the sensitive question bias, where participants may disclose a false result out of embarrassment. Questions like âwhat is your shoeâs sizeâ are affected by the misinterpretation bias due to not standardizing results (is the shoe size to be measured to European or American standard?). The survey is 49 questions long, leading to survey fatigue bias where the participants feel tired from doing such a long survey and start answering later questions with less care than the first ones. This list is not an exhaustive list of possible biases but a list that the author believes to be most significant.

As a result, some questions can be improved for better data collection in the future. Questions on numerical values like âageâ and âheightâ should have data validation for integer values only to avoid results like â20+â. Questions like âcountryâ should be a radio button list to avoid discrepancies like âAustraliaâ and âAustralia!â. The question on gender should also be a radio button list instead of free form response to avoid offensive inputs and standardization issues. Questions like âallergiesâ should be of type multiple choices response or integer validation. Questions like the one about shoe size should specify the scale it is using to avoid confusion. This list is not an exhaustive list of possible fixes but a list that the author believes to be most significant.

From these result, this report will attempt to identify traits that are most indicative of being a good team member, hoping to help others in choosing their own team for the upcoming group assignment for DATA2x02.

1.1 Data Wrangling

The calculations in this report were performed in R (R Core Team 2024) within the Rmarkdown environment (Xie, Allaire, and Grolemund 2018) for reproducibility. Data wrangling was performed in base R and the tidyverse (Wickham et al. 2019) and janitor (Firke 2023). Graphs were produced with ggplot2 (Wickham et al. 2019) except for the missing value visualization made with the visdat package (Tierney 2023) and the Q-Q plots which were made with the ggpubr package (Kassambara 2023). Tables were made using the gt package (Iannone et al. 2024) and cleaning matrices into data frame used the reshape2 package (Wickham 2020). The patchwork package was used to display plots side by side (Pedersen 2024).

Names of the variables were cleaned and shortened. Responses values are also cleaned, shortened and categorized. The gender variable cleaning and renaming is based on Tarr (2024a). Missing and nonsensical values were not removed at this stage, but will dealt with on a case by case basis, to conserve as much data as possible for analysis.

2 Results

2.1 Is WAM significantly different at the p < 0.05 level between DATA2002 and DATA2902 students?

From the table FigureÂ 3, we can see that the mean WAM of DATA2902 students is slightly higher. This fits the rationale of some people who enrolled in DATA2902 despite struggling with DATA1001 - that their lab mates would have higher WAM and therefore be better teammates who can carry them.

Code 
# Remove rows where 'wam' and 'enrolled_unit' is NA or nonsensical
data2x02_wam_cohort <- data2x02 %>% filter(!is.na(wam) & !is.na(enrolled_unit))
# WAM of less than 50 is nonsensical, shouldn't pass to take DATA2x02
data2x02_wam_cohort <- data2x02_wam_cohort %>% filter(wam >= 50)
data2x02_wam_cohort$enrolled_unit <- factor(data2x02_wam_cohort$enrolled_unit)

# Create table
formatted = data2x02_wam_cohort %>% select(wam, enrolled_unit) %>% group_by(enrolled_unit) %>%
  summarise(n = n(),
            Mean = mean(wam) %>% signif(2),
            SD = sd(wam) %>% signif(2)
            )
colnames(formatted)[colnames(formatted) == 'enrolled_unit'] <- 'Enrolled unit'
knitr::kable(formatted)

From the double Q-Q plot FigureÂ 4, we can see that the two samples are not quite normal, having deviations near both ends of the line. This means that we should not assume normality. From the side-by-side violin plot FigureÂ 4, we can see that the distribution of WAM for both cohorts can be considered symmetric but with unequal variances. DATA2002âs distribution is much more symmetric compared to DATA2902, which has a longer left tail. From this observation, we can assume symmetry of distribution. As a result, we should conduct a rank-sum test.

Code 
data2x02_wam_cohort_2002 = data2x02_wam_cohort %>% filter(enrolled_unit == "DATA2002")
data2x02_wam_cohort_2902 = data2x02_wam_cohort %>% filter(enrolled_unit == "DATA2902")

# Side-by-side violin plots comparing WAM by Unit
p1 <-  ggplot(data2x02_wam_cohort, aes(x = enrolled_unit, y = wam, fill = enrolled_unit, color = enrolled_unit)) +
  geom_violin(trim = FALSE, width = 0.9, fill = "white") +
  labs(title = "Violin plot of WAM by Unit",
       x = "Unit enrolled",
       y = "WAM",
       fill = "Unit enrolled", 
       color = "Unit enrolled") +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.5) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("purple","darkorange")) + 
  theme(
    panel.background = element_rect(fill = "lightgrey", color = NA),
    panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "white"),
    panel.grid.minor = element_line(color = "white")
  )

# Double Q-Q plot
p2 <-  ggqqplot(data2x02_wam_cohort, x = "wam", facet.by = "enrolled_unit") + labs(title = "WAM Q-Q plot")

p1 + p2 + plot_annotation(tag_levels = 'A')
Code 
myTest <- wilcox.test(wam ~ enrolled_unit, data = data2x02_wam_cohort, alternative = "less")

  1. Hypothesis: Let \(\mu_A\) and \(\mu_B\) be the population mean WAM for DATA2002 and DATA2902 students respectively. \(H_0\): \(\mu_A\) = \(\mu_B\) vs \(H_1\): \(\mu_A < \mu_B\)

  2. Assumptions: The two populations have a symmetrical distribution (Distributions have symmetry in the violin plots in the left panel of FigureÂ 4).

  3. Test statistic: \(W = R_1 + R_2 + \cdots + R_{n_A}\sim WRS(n_A, n_B)\) where \(n_A =\) 208, \(n_B =\) 50 and \(WRS\) as the Wilcoxon rank sum distribution.

  4. Observed test statistic: \(w_0\) = 2390

  5. p-value: \(P(WRS(208, 50) \le 2390) <0.001\)

  6. Decision: Since the p-value is less than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis and conclude there is a significant difference in the mean WAM between DATA2002 and DATA2902 students, with DATA2902 students having on average higher WAM, a desirable characteristic in a teammate.

2.2 Is grade aim and assignment submission preferences dependent at the p < 0.05 level?

Many people believe that there is a relationship between your approach to assignment submission and your grade aim. It is common sense to assume that someone who aims toward a higher score would be more proactive in their study and therefore would like to submit early. We test this claim at the p = 0.05 significant level.

Code 
# Filter out NA values and remove nonsensical data
data2x02_tg_ap <- data2x02 %>% filter(!is.na(target_grade) & !is.na(assignment_preference))

# Unlikely that someone is aiming to fail
data2x02_tg_ap <- data2x02_tg_ap %>% filter(!(target_grade == 'Fail'))

# Ordering target_grade
data2x02_tg_ap$target_grade <- factor(data2x02_tg_ap$target_grade, levels = c("Pass", "Distinction", "High Distinction"), ordered = TRUE)

# Reassigning assignment preference values to "cram" and "no cram"
data2x02_tg_ap$assignment_preference <- ifelse(data2x02_tg_ap$assignment_preference == "cram", "cram", "no cram")

# Create a contingency tables
contingency_table <- table(data2x02_tg_ap$target_grade, data2x02_tg_ap$assignment_preference)
knitr::kable(contingency_table)
Code 
# Create a mosaic plot
mosaicplot(contingency_table, main = "Mosaic Plot of grade aim vs assignment preferences",
           xlab = "Grade aim", ylab = "Assignment preferences", col = c("purple","darkorange"))
Code 
# Chi-Square test of independence
chi_test_result <- chisq.test(contingency_table)
# Extract the expected values, check for > 5 status
expected <- chi_test_result$expected
knitr::kable(expected > 5)
cram no cram
Pass FALSE TRUE
Distinction TRUE TRUE
High Distinction TRUE TRUE

Table of expected values > 5 status

  1. Hypothesis: \(H_0:\) assignment preferences and grade aim is independent vs \(H_1:\) There is dependence between assignment preferences and grade aim.

  2. Assumptions: From the table generated above, we can conclude that Cochranâs assumption is valid here as the number of cells with a expected value of lower than 5 is less than 20%. Therefore, Pearsonâs Chi-square test is preferred.

  3. Test statistic: \(T = \sum_{i=1}^{a} \sum_{j=1}^{b} \frac{(O_{ij} - E_{ij})^2}{E_{ij}}\). Under \(H_0, T \sim \chi^2_{(a-1)(b-1)}\).

Code 
t0 <- chisq.test(contingency_table)
  1. Observed test statistic: \(t_0 =\) 9.94 with 2 degrees of freedom
Code 
# Randomly create tables for Chi-square distribution
set.seed(1)
B = 10000

x_list = r2dtable(n = B, 
                  r = rowSums(contingency_table),
                  c = colSums(contingency_table))

rnd.chisq = numeric(B) 

for (i in 1:B) {   
  rnd.chisq[i] = chisq.test(x_list[[i]])$statistic 
}

# Create histogram
hist(rnd.chisq, 
     col = "orange",
     xlab=expression(chi^2 ~ "Values"),
     main = bquote(chi^2 ~ "Distribution with df =" ~ .(t0$parameter)))

abline(v = signif(t0$statistic,3), col = "purple", lwd = 2) 

text(x = signif(t0$statistic, 3), 
     y = max(hist(rnd.chisq, plot = FALSE)$counts) * 0.95,
     labels = round(signif(t0$statistic, 3), 2), 
     col = "purple", 
     pos = 4,
     cex = 1.2)

  1. p-value: \(P(\chi^2_2 \ge 9.94) = 0.007\)

  2. Decision: Reject in \(H_0\) favor of \(H_1\), as the observed p-value, 0.007, is smaller than the 5% critical threshold. The data supports the belief that there is dependency between assignment preferences and grade aim. Looking at the mosaic plot FigureÂ 6, we can see that students who took a more proactive approach to assignment submission are more likely to have higher grade aim, a desirable characteristic in a teammate.

2.3 Is there a significant difference in hours of study at the p-value = 0.05 level between nationality, controlled for gender?

Since the group project holds such weight, finding teammates is incredibly important. However, this may lead to discrimination against people of different nationalities and gender, with some groups being favored and others shunned. As a result, this report would like to amend this problem by checking whether these biases have any basis.

We categorize nationality into continents due to the low cell counts of some countries before taking a look at the two most prominent groups here (Oceania and Asia). We divide study hours per week into quantiles for ease of analysis.

Code 
# Filter out NA values and remove nonsensical data
data2x02_ngh <- data2x02 %>% filter(!is.na(gender_clean) & !is.na(country_of_birth) & !is.na(weekly_study_hours))

# Unlikely to have students from North Korea, most people should study at least 2 hours a day due to mandatory university lectures and less than 10 hours a day to have 6 hours for rest and other activities.
data2x02_ngh <- data2x02_ngh %>% filter(country_of_birth != "North Korea")
data2x02_ngh <- data2x02_ngh %>% filter(14 < weekly_study_hours & weekly_study_hours < 70)


# Adding continent category
data2x02_ngh$continent[data2x02_ngh$country_of_birth == "australia"] <- "Oceania"
data2x02_ngh$continent[data2x02_ngh$country_of_birth == "new zealand"] <- "Oceania"

data2x02_ngh$continent[data2x02_ngh$country_of_birth %in% c("china", "india", "malaysia", "pakistan", "thailand", 
                                               "indonesia", "vietnam", "hongkong", "myanmar", 
                                               "singapore", "bangladesh", "uae", "israel", 
                                               "south korea", "taiwan", "japan", "north korea", 
                                               "philippines")] <- "Asia"

data2x02_ngh$continent[data2x02_ngh$country_of_birth %in% c("usa", "america")] <- "North America"

data2x02_ngh$continent[data2x02_ngh$country_of_birth %in% c("england", "denmark", "germany", "france")] <- "Europe"

data2x02_ngh$continent[data2x02_ngh$country_of_birth == "south africa"] <- "Africa"

# Adding study hours quantiles
data2x02_ngh$quartile <- cut(
  data2x02_ngh$weekly_study_hours, 
  breaks = quantile(data2x02_ngh$weekly_study_hours, probs = seq(0, 1, by = 1/4), na.rm = TRUE), 
  include.lowest = TRUE, 
  labels = c("Q1", "Q2", "Q3", "Q4")
)

2.3.1 Male dataset

Code 
chiqMF <- chisq.test(contingency_table1)

  1. Hypotheses: \(H_0\): The proportion of studentsâ study hours quantiles are the same for both male students from Oceania and Asia vs \(H_1\): The ratio are not the same.

  2. Assumptions: \(e_i\) = \(np_i \ge 5\), which we have checked and confirmed to be true for more than 80% of all cells (FigureÂ 10).

  3. Test statistic: \(T = \sum_{i=1}^{a} \sum_{j=1}^{b} \frac{(O_{ij} - E_{ij})^2}{E_{ij}}\). Under \(H_0, T \sim \chi^2_{(a-1)(b-1)}\).

  4. Observed test statistic: \(t_0\) = 11

Code 
# Randomly create tables for Chi-square distribution

set.seed(1)
B = 10000

x_list = r2dtable(n = B, 
                  r = rowSums(contingency_table1),
                  c = colSums(contingency_table1))

rnd.chisq = numeric(B) 

for (i in 1:B) {   
  rnd.chisq[i] = chisq.test(x_list[[i]])$statistic 
}

# Make histogram
hist(rnd.chisq, 
     col = "orange",
     xlab=expression(chi^2 ~ "Values"),
     main = bquote(chi^2 ~ "Distribution with df =" ~ .(chiqMF$parameter)))

abline(v = signif(chiqMF$statistic,3), col = "purple", lwd = 2) 

text(x = signif(chiqMF$statistic, 3), 
     y = max(hist(rnd.chisq, plot = FALSE)$counts) * 0.95,
     labels = round(signif(chiqMF$statistic, 3), 2), 
     col = "purple", 
     pos = 4,
     cex = 1.2)

  1. p-value: \(P(\chi^2_3 \ge\) 11 ) = 0.00945

  2. Decision: Since the p-value is much smaller than the 5% threshold, we reject \(H_0\) and accept that there are evidence supporting the claim that the study hours quantiles ratio are not the same between Asia and Oceania. Looking at the heat map on the left of (FigureÂ 12), we see evidence that Male Asian students are more likely to report higher study hours per week than their Oceania peers, a preferred characteristic in teammates.

  1. Hypotheses: \(H_0\): The proportion of studentsâ study hours quantiles are the same for both female students from Oceania and Asia vs \(H_1\): The ratio are not the same.

  2. Assumptions: Monte Carlo simulations allow this test to be non-parametric and requires no assumptions.

  3. Test statistic: \(T = \sum_{i=1}^{a} \sum_{j=1}^{b} \frac{(O_{ij} - E_{ij})^2}{E_{ij}}\).

  4. Observed test statistic: \(t_0\) = 4.1, \(df = NA\)

3 Conclusion

Group projects are an important part of DATA2x02, therefore many people have an interest in seeking out the best teammates.

Here we have shown that there was a significant difference in mean WAM between DATA2002 and DATA2902 students, implying that DATA2902 students on average can be better teammates if we use WAM as an indicator of success.

We also have shown a relationship between assignment submission preference and grade aim, where students who took a more proactive approach to submission are more likely to aim for higher grade, also an indicator for being a good teammate.

However, the conclusion for whether there is any valid reason to choose teammates by their nationality is muddled. For female teammates, there seems to be no significant difference while for male teammates, Asian students often report higher study hours per week, an indicator for being a good teammate. Whether this difference is due to culture or simply response bias (most likely sensitive question) is unclear and beyond the scope of this report, warranting further investigation.

## Introduction

@DATA2x02 looked at the online survey completed voluntarily by the 2024 S2 cohort of DATA2x02, totaling 313 responses for 49 question. The end result is stored in a .xlsx file, exported from Google form. [@fig-survey].
The responses are unlikely to be a completely random sample of DATA2x02 students. Since the survey is completed voluntarily on Edstem, the survey is subject to non-random participation. This survey may over-represent students who are interested in the subject and those who frequently open their Ed discussions.

Aside from the bias mentioned above, many variables in this survey are subject to other biases. Questions regarding WAM and others of similar sensitive nature are subject to the sensitive question bias, where participants may disclose a false result out of embarrassment. Questions like "what is your shoe's size" are affected by the misinterpretation bias due to not standardizing results (is the shoe size to be measured to European or American standard?). The survey is 49 questions long, leading to survey fatigue bias where the participants feel tired from doing such a long survey and start answering later questions with less care than the first ones. This list is not an exhaustive list of possible biases but a list that the author believes to be most significant.

As a result, some questions can be improved for better data collection in the future. Questions on numerical values like "age" and "height" should have data validation for integer values only to avoid results like "20+". Questions like "country" should be a radio button list to avoid discrepancies like "Australia" and "Australia!". The question on gender should also be a radio button list instead of free form response to avoid offensive inputs and standardization issues. Questions like "allergies" should be of type multiple choices response or integer validation. Questions like the one about shoe size should specify the scale it is using to avoid confusion. This list is not an exhaustive list of possible fixes but a list that the author believes to be most significant.

From these result, this report will attempt to identify traits that are most indicative of being a good team member, hoping to help others in choosing their own team for the upcoming group assignment for DATA2x02.

```{r fig-survey, echo = FALSE, out.width= '45%', out.height= '20%', fig.cap = "The survey on Google Form", fig.show='hold', fig.align='center'} 
knitr::include_graphics("images/survey.png")

### Data Wrangling

The calculations in this report were performed in R [@R-base] within the Rmarkdown environment [@rmarkdown2018] for reproducibility. Data wrangling was performed in base R and the tidyverse [@tidyverse2019] and janitor [@R-janitor]. Graphs were produced with ggplot2 [@tidyverse2019] except for the missing value visualization made with the visdat package [@R-visdat] and the Q-Q plots which were made with the ggpubr package [@R-ggpubr]. Tables were made using the gt package [@R-gt] and cleaning matrices into data frame used the reshape2 package [@R-reshape2]. The patchwork package was used to display plots side by side [@R-patchwork].

Names of the variables were cleaned and shortened. Responses values are also cleaned, shortened and categorized. The gender variable cleaning and renaming is based on @tarr2024. Missing and nonsensical values were not removed at this stage, but will dealt with on a case by case basis, to conserve as much data as possible for analysis.

## Results

### Is WAM significantly different at the p < 0.05 level between *DATA2002* and *DATA2902* students?

From the table @fig-table-wam, we can see that the mean WAM of *DATA2902 students* is slightly higher. This fits the rationale of some people who enrolled in DATA2902 despite struggling with DATA1001 - that their lab mates would have higher WAM and therefore be better teammates who can carry them.

```{r fig-table-wam, fig.asp=0.5, out.width= "80%", warning=FALSE, message=FALSE, fig.cap= "Table of WAM mean and sd, separated by unit"}
# Remove rows where 'wam' and 'enrolled_unit' is NA or nonsensical
data2x02_wam_cohort <- data2x02 %>% filter(!is.na(wam) & !is.na(enrolled_unit))
# WAM of less than 50 is nonsensical, shouldn't pass to take DATA2x02
data2x02_wam_cohort <- data2x02_wam_cohort %>% filter(wam >= 50)
data2x02_wam_cohort$enrolled_unit <- factor(data2x02_wam_cohort$enrolled_unit)

# Create table
formatted = data2x02_wam_cohort %>% select(wam, enrolled_unit) %>% group_by(enrolled_unit) %>%
  summarise(n = n(),
            Mean = mean(wam) %>% signif(2),
            SD = sd(wam) %>% signif(2)
            )
colnames(formatted)[colnames(formatted) == 'enrolled_unit'] <- 'Enrolled unit'
knitr::kable(formatted)
```

From the double Q-Q plot @fig-double, we can see that the two samples are not quite normal, having deviations near both ends of the line. This means that we should not assume normality. From the side-by-side violin plot @fig-double, we can see that the distribution of WAM for both cohorts can be considered symmetric but with unequal variances. *DATA2002*'s distribution is much more symmetric compared to *DATA2902*, which has a longer left tail. From this observation, we can assume symmetry of distribution. As a result, we should conduct a rank-sum test.

```{r fig-double, fig.asp=0.5, out.width= "100%", warning=FALSE, message=FALSE, fig.cap= "WAM distribution, checking for normality and symmetry **A**: Violin plot **B**: Q-Q plot"}

data2x02_wam_cohort_2002 = data2x02_wam_cohort %>% filter(enrolled_unit == "DATA2002")
data2x02_wam_cohort_2902 = data2x02_wam_cohort %>% filter(enrolled_unit == "DATA2902")

# Side-by-side violin plots comparing WAM by Unit
p1 <-  ggplot(data2x02_wam_cohort, aes(x = enrolled_unit, y = wam, fill = enrolled_unit, color = enrolled_unit)) +
  geom_violin(trim = FALSE, width = 0.9, fill = "white") +
  labs(title = "Violin plot of WAM by Unit",
       x = "Unit enrolled",
       y = "WAM",
       fill = "Unit enrolled", 
       color = "Unit enrolled") +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.5) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("purple","darkorange")) + 
  theme(
    panel.background = element_rect(fill = "lightgrey", color = NA),
    panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "white"),
    panel.grid.minor = element_line(color = "white")
  )

# Double Q-Q plot
p2 <-  ggqqplot(data2x02_wam_cohort, x = "wam", facet.by = "enrolled_unit") + labs(title = "WAM Q-Q plot")

p1 + p2 + plot_annotation(tag_levels = 'A')
```

```{r, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE}
myTest <- wilcox.test(wam ~ enrolled_unit, data = data2x02_wam_cohort, alternative = "less")
```

1. **Hypothesis**:  Let $\mu_A$ and $\mu_B$ be the population mean WAM for *DATA2002* and *DATA2902* students respectively.
$H_0$: $\mu_A$ = $\mu_B$ vs $H_1$: $\mu_A < \mu_B$

2. **Assumptions**: The two populations have a symmetrical distribution (Distributions have symmetry in the violin plots in the left panel of @fig-double).

3. **Test statistic**: $W = R_1 + R_2 + \cdots + R_{n_A}\sim WRS(n_A, n_B)$ where $n_A =$ `r formatted$n[1]`, $n_B =$ `r formatted$n[2]` and $WRS$ as the Wilcoxon rank sum distribution.

4. **Observed test statistic**: $w_0$ = `r signif(myTest$statistic,3)`

5. **p-value**: $P(WRS(`r formatted$n[1]`, `r formatted$n[2]`) \le `r signif(myTest$statistic,3)`)  `r format.pval(myTest$p.value,digits = 2, eps = 0.001)`$

6. **Decision**: Since the p-value is less than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis and conclude there is a significant difference in the mean WAM between *DATA2002* and *DATA2902* students, with *DATA2902* students having on average higher WAM, a desirable characteristic in a teammate.

### Is grade aim and assignment submission preferences dependent at the p < 0.05 level?

Many people believe that there is a relationship between your approach to assignment submission and your grade aim. It is common sense to assume that someone who aims toward a higher score would be more proactive in their study and therefore would like to submit early. We test this claim at the p = 0.05 significant level.

```{r fig-table-tgap, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE, fig.asp=0.5, out.width= "80%", warning=FALSE, message=FALSE, fig.cap= "Table of grade aim and assignment preferences frequency"}

# Filter out NA values and remove nonsensical data
data2x02_tg_ap <- data2x02 %>% filter(!is.na(target_grade) & !is.na(assignment_preference))

# Unlikely that someone is aiming to fail
data2x02_tg_ap <- data2x02_tg_ap %>% filter(!(target_grade == 'Fail'))

# Ordering target_grade
data2x02_tg_ap$target_grade <- factor(data2x02_tg_ap$target_grade, levels = c("Pass", "Distinction", "High Distinction"), ordered = TRUE)

# Reassigning assignment preference values to "cram" and "no cram"
data2x02_tg_ap$assignment_preference <- ifelse(data2x02_tg_ap$assignment_preference == "cram", "cram", "no cram")

# Create a contingency tables
contingency_table <- table(data2x02_tg_ap$target_grade, data2x02_tg_ap$assignment_preference)
knitr::kable(contingency_table)
```
```{r fig-mosaic, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE, fig.asp=0.5, out.width= "80%", fig.cap= "Mosaic plot of grade aim and assignment preferences frequency"}
# Create a mosaic plot
mosaicplot(contingency_table, main = "Mosaic Plot of grade aim vs assignment preferences",
           xlab = "Grade aim", ylab = "Assignment preferences", col = c("purple","darkorange"))
```

```{r fig-cochran, results = 'asis', warning=FALSE, fig.asp=0.5, out.width= "80%", warning=FALSE, message=FALSE, fig.cap= "Table of expected values > 5 status"}
# Chi-Square test of independence
chi_test_result <- chisq.test(contingency_table)
# Extract the expected values, check for > 5 status
expected <- chi_test_result$expected
knitr::kable(expected > 5)
```

1. **Hypothesis:** $H_0:$ assignment preferences and grade aim is independent vs $H_1:$ There is dependence between assignment preferences and grade aim.

2. **Assumptions:** From the table generated above, we can conclude that Cochran's assumption is valid here as the number of cells with a expected value of lower than 5 is less than 20%. Therefore, Pearson's Chi-square test is preferred.

3. **Test statistic:** $T = \sum_{i=1}^{a} \sum_{j=1}^{b} \frac{(O_{ij} - E_{ij})^2}{E_{ij}}$. Under $H_0, T \sim \chi^2_{(a-1)(b-1)}$.
```{r, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE}
t0 <- chisq.test(contingency_table)
```

4. **Observed test statistic:** $t_0 =$ `r signif(t0$statistic,3)` with `r t0$parameter` degrees of freedom

```{r fig-plot, warning = FALSE, message=FALSE, fig.cap= expression(chi^2 ~ "Distribution")}
# Randomly create tables for Chi-square distribution
set.seed(1)
B = 10000

x_list = r2dtable(n = B, 
                  r = rowSums(contingency_table),
                  c = colSums(contingency_table))

rnd.chisq = numeric(B) 

for (i in 1:B) {   
  rnd.chisq[i] = chisq.test(x_list[[i]])$statistic 
}

# Create histogram
hist(rnd.chisq, 
     col = "orange",
     xlab=expression(chi^2 ~ "Values"),
     main = bquote(chi^2 ~ "Distribution with df =" ~ .(t0$parameter)))

abline(v = signif(t0$statistic,3), col = "purple", lwd = 2) 

text(x = signif(t0$statistic, 3), 
     y = max(hist(rnd.chisq, plot = FALSE)$counts) * 0.95,
     labels = round(signif(t0$statistic, 3), 2), 
     col = "purple", 
     pos = 4,
     cex = 1.2)
```

5. **p-value**: $P(\chi^2_2 \ge `r signif(t0$statistic,3)`) =  `r  format.pval(t0$p.value,digits = 2, eps = 0.001)`$

6. **Decision**: Reject in $H_0$ favor of $H_1$, as the observed p-value, `r  format.pval(t0$p.value,digits = 2, eps = 0.001)`, is smaller than the 5% critical threshold. The data supports the belief that there is dependency between assignment preferences and grade aim. Looking at the mosaic plot @fig-mosaic, we can see that students who took a more proactive approach to assignment submission are more likely to have higher grade aim, a desirable characteristic in a teammate.


### Is there a significant difference in hours of study at the p-value = 0.05 level between nationality, controlled for gender?

Since the group project holds such weight, finding teammates is incredibly important. However, this may lead to discrimination against people of different nationalities and gender, with some groups being favored and others shunned. As a result, this report would like to amend this problem by checking whether these biases have any basis.

We categorize nationality into continents due to the low cell counts of some countries before taking a look at the two most prominent groups here (Oceania and Asia). We divide study hours per week into quantiles for ease of analysis.

```{r, message = FALSE, warning= FALSE}
# Filter out NA values and remove nonsensical data
data2x02_ngh <- data2x02 %>% filter(!is.na(gender_clean) & !is.na(country_of_birth) & !is.na(weekly_study_hours))

# Unlikely to have students from North Korea, most people should study at least 2 hours a day due to mandatory university lectures and less than 10 hours a day to have 6 hours for rest and other activities.
data2x02_ngh <- data2x02_ngh %>% filter(country_of_birth != "North Korea")
data2x02_ngh <- data2x02_ngh %>% filter(14 < weekly_study_hours & weekly_study_hours < 70)


# Adding continent category
data2x02_ngh$continent[data2x02_ngh$country_of_birth == "australia"] <- "Oceania"
data2x02_ngh$continent[data2x02_ngh$country_of_birth == "new zealand"] <- "Oceania"

data2x02_ngh$continent[data2x02_ngh$country_of_birth %in% c("china", "india", "malaysia", "pakistan", "thailand", 
                                               "indonesia", "vietnam", "hongkong", "myanmar", 
                                               "singapore", "bangladesh", "uae", "israel", 
                                               "south korea", "taiwan", "japan", "north korea", 
                                               "philippines")] <- "Asia"

data2x02_ngh$continent[data2x02_ngh$country_of_birth %in% c("usa", "america")] <- "North America"

data2x02_ngh$continent[data2x02_ngh$country_of_birth %in% c("england", "denmark", "germany", "france")] <- "Europe"

data2x02_ngh$continent[data2x02_ngh$country_of_birth == "south africa"] <- "Africa"

# Adding study hours quantiles
data2x02_ngh$quartile <- cut(
  data2x02_ngh$weekly_study_hours, 
  breaks = quantile(data2x02_ngh$weekly_study_hours, probs = seq(0, 1, by = 1/4), na.rm = TRUE), 
  include.lowest = TRUE, 
  labels = c("Q1", "Q2", "Q3", "Q4")
)
```

```{r fig-table-tgap-m, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE, fig.asp=0.5, out.width= "80%", warning=FALSE, message=FALSE, fig.cap= "Table of continents and study hours per week count for male students"}
# Split data into male and female data sets
data2x02_ngh_m <- data2x02_ngh %>% filter(gender_clean == "man")
data2x02_ngh_f <- data2x02_ngh %>% filter(gender_clean == "woman")

# Filter for Oceanic and Asian students
subset_data <- subset(data2x02_ngh_m, continent %in% c("Asia", "Oceania"))

# Create a contingency table for male data set

knitr::kable(contingency_table1)
```


```{r fig-table-tgap-f, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE, fig.asp=0.5, out.width= "80%", warning=FALSE, message=FALSE, fig.cap= "Table of continents and study hours per week count for female students"}

subset_data <- subset(data2x02_ngh_f, continent %in% c("Asia", "Oceania"))

```
From the tables generated, we can conclude that Cochran's assumption is valid for the male data set as less than 20% of the cells have a expected value of lower than 5 (@@fig-table-exp-m) but not for the female data set (@fig-table-exp-f). Therefore, the female data set will be analysed using Monte Carlo simulation instead.

```{r fig-table-exp-m, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE, fig.asp=0.5, out.width= "80%", warning=FALSE, message=FALSE, fig.cap= "Table of Chi-square expected values > 5 status for male students"}

chi_test_result1 <- chisq.test(contingency_table1)

# Extract the expected values, check for > 5 status
expected1 <- chi_test_result1$expected > 5

```


```{r fig-table-exp-f, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE, fig.asp=0.5, out.width= "80%", warning=FALSE, message=FALSE, fig.cap= "Table of Chi-square expected values > 5 status for female students"}
# Chi-Square test of independence for female data set
chi_test_result2 <- chisq.test(contingency_table2)

# Extract the expected values, check for > 5 status

The heat maps generated here (@fig-heatmaps) show a general trend of students from Oceania more often reporting themselves from the lowest quantile of study hours than expected and students from Asia reporting themselves more frequently from higher quantiles than expected.

```{r fig-heatmaps, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE, fig.asp=0.5, out.width= "80%", warning=FALSE, message=FALSE, fig.cap= "Heat maps of Chi-square tests residuals for male and female student of Oceania and Asia **A**: Male **B**: Female"}
# Melting matrices into data frames

#### Male dataset

```{r, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE}
chiqMF <- chisq.test(contingency_table1)
```

1. **Hypotheses**: $H_0$: The proportion of students' study hours quantiles are the same for both male students from Oceania and Asia vs $H_1$: The ratio are not the same.

2. **Assumptions**: $e_i$ = $np_i \ge 5$, which we have checked and confirmed to be true for more than 80% of all cells (@fig-table-exp-m).

3. **Test statistic**: $T = \sum_{i=1}^{a} \sum_{j=1}^{b} \frac{(O_{ij} - E_{ij})^2}{E_{ij}}$. Under $H_0, T \sim \chi^2_{(a-1)(b-1)}$.

4. **Observed test statistic**: $t_0$ = `r signif(chiqMF$statistic,2)`

```{r fig-plot-1, warning = FALSE, message=FALSE, fig.cap= expression(chi^2 ~ "Distribution")}
# Randomly create tables for Chi-square distribution

set.seed(1)
B = 10000

x_list = r2dtable(n = B, 
                  r = rowSums(contingency_table1),
                  c = colSums(contingency_table1))

rnd.chisq = numeric(B) 

for (i in 1:B) {   
  rnd.chisq[i] = chisq.test(x_list[[i]])$statistic 
}

# Make histogram
hist(rnd.chisq, 
     col = "orange",
     xlab=expression(chi^2 ~ "Values"),
     main = bquote(chi^2 ~ "Distribution with df =" ~ .(chiqMF$parameter)))

abline(v = signif(chiqMF$statistic,3), col = "purple", lwd = 2) 

text(x = signif(chiqMF$statistic, 3), 
     y = max(hist(rnd.chisq, plot = FALSE)$counts) * 0.95,
     labels = round(signif(chiqMF$statistic, 3), 2), 
     col = "purple", 
     pos = 4,
     cex = 1.2)
```
5. **p-value**: $P(\chi^2_3 \ge$ `r signif(chiqMF$statistic,2)` ) = `r format.pval(chiqMF$p.value,digits = 3, eps = 0.001)`

6. **Decision**: Since the p-value is much smaller than the 5% threshold, we reject $H_0$ and accept that there are evidence supporting the claim that the study hours quantiles ratio are not the same between Asia and Oceania. Looking at the heat map on the left of (@fig-heatmaps), we see evidence that Male Asian students are more likely to report higher study hours per week than their Oceania peers, a preferred characteristic in teammates. 

#### Female dataset

```{r, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE}
set.seed(1)
chiqMF <- chisq.test(contingency_table2, simulate.p.value = TRUE, B = 20000)
```

1. **Hypotheses**: $H_0$: The proportion of students' study hours quantiles are the same for both female students from Oceania and Asia vs $H_1$: The ratio are not the same.

2. **Assumptions**: Monte Carlo simulations allow this test to be non-parametric and requires no assumptions.

3. **Test statistic**: $T = \sum_{i=1}^{a} \sum_{j=1}^{b} \frac{(O_{ij} - E_{ij})^2}{E_{ij}}$.

4. **Observed test statistic**: $t_0$ = `r signif(chiqMF$statistic,2)`, $df = NA$

```{r fig-plot-2, warning = FALSE, message=FALSE, fig.cap= expression(chi^2 ~ "Distribution")}
# Randomly create tables for Chi-square distribution
set.seed(1)
B = 10000

x_list = r2dtable(n = B, 
                  r = rowSums(contingency_table2),
                  c = colSums(contingency_table2))

rnd.chisq = numeric(B) 

for (i in 1:B) {   
  rnd.chisq[i] = chisq.test(x_list[[i]])$statistic 
}

# Create histogram
hist(rnd.chisq, 
     col = "orange",
     xlab=expression(chi^2 ~ "Values"),

     col = "purple", 
     pos = 4,

```

5. **p-value**: $P(\chi^2_{df} \ge$ `r signif(chiqMF$statistic,2)` ) = `r format.pval(chiqMF$p.value,digits = 3, eps = 0.001)`

6. **Decision**: Since the p-value is larger than the threshold value of 5%, we accept $H_0$ and conclude that there is not enough evidence to reject the claim that the proportion of students' study hours quantiles are the same for both female students from Oceania and Asia.

## Conclusion

Group projects are an important part of DATA2x02, therefore many people have an interest in seeking out the best teammates.

Here we have shown that there was a significant difference in mean WAM between DATA2002 and DATA2902 students, implying that DATA2902 students on average can be better teammates if we use WAM as an indicator of success.

We also have shown a relationship between assignment submission preference and grade aim, where students who took a more proactive approach to submission are more likely to aim for higher grade, also an indicator for being a good teammate.

However, the conclusion for whether there is any valid reason to choose teammates by their nationality is muddled. For female teammates, there seems to be no significant difference while for male teammates, Asian students often report higher study hours per week, an indicator for being a good teammate. Whether this difference is due to culture or simply response bias (most likely sensitive question) is unclear and beyond the scope of this report, warranting further investigation.
